Continued Firmware Review — Part 2

🔴 BUGS (Continued)
22. GPS coordinate precision loss — float truncation before double storage
In get_gps_coordinates():
cppfloat lat, lon;  // float declared
sscanf(..., "%f,%f,", ..., &lat, &lon);
lati = lat;  // assigned to RTC_DATA_ATTR double
longi = lon;
lati/longi are double in RTC RAM, but the intermediate float has only ~7 significant digits. A coordinate like 12.989436 round-trips through float as 12.9894361 — an error of about 0.02m, which is acceptable. However get_lat_long_date_time() (used for SMS status) correctly uses %lf directly into lati/longi. The inconsistency is a latent correctness issue; use %lf and a double local variable in get_gps_coordinates() as well.

23. signature.txt write in send_http_data() is NOT atomic
cppFile fileTemp2 = SPIFFS.open("/signature.txt", FILE_WRITE);
fileTemp2.print(signature);
fileTemp2.close();
If power is lost mid-write, signature.txt is truncated/corrupt. The resync_time() path uses a .tmp → rename atomic pattern correctly, but the HTTP success path does not. A corrupt signature causes the scheduler to misidentify the last-recorded sample and produce duplicate or gap-filled records on the next boot.
Fix: Use /signature.tmp → rename here too, same as resync_time().

24. waitForResponse() 2KB local buffer causes deep stack risk
cppString waitForResponse(String expectedResponse, int timeout) {
  char buf[2048];  // 2KB on stack!
The GPRS task has a 16KB stack. At maximum call nesting — gprs() → send_http_data() → prepare_data_and_send() → send_at_cmd_data() → waitForResponse() — plus each function's own local variables (char fallbackUrl[150], char gprs_xmit_buf[300], String response, etc.), stack depth at this level is approximately 2KB (waitForResponse) + 300 + 150 + ~500 = ~3KB for locals. The total GPRS task frame depth for this call chain is conservatively 6–7KB, leaving only ~9KB of headroom for the RTOS overhead and remaining call frames. If send_http_data() calls verify_bearer_or_recover() which itself calls start_gprs() which calls waitForResponse(), another 2KB buffer is pushed. On the worst-case OTA path, 4+ nested waitForResponse() calls are active simultaneously.
Fix: Make buf static in waitForResponse(). Since this is called only from the modem-owning GPRS task sequentially, static is safe and eliminates stack risk entirely:
cppstatic char buf[2048];

25. content = file1.readString() allocates entire FTP file on heap
In send_ftp_file() and the send_unsent path:
cppcontent = file1.readString(); // Read the rest of the file
This loads the entire FTP file (potentially 100KB per the trim logic) into a single heap-allocated String. At 100KB allocation on a fragmented heap, this will fail with content being empty, and the AT+FSWRITE will silently write nothing to the modem FS. The code doesn't check content.length() == 0 before writing.
Fix: Stream the FTP file to the modem in 256-byte chunks using file.read(buf, 256) inside the CONNECT window, rather than a single readString(). This is the correct pattern for cellular data transfer.

🔴 SERVER-SIDE SECURITY BUGS
26. /builds/{filename} endpoint has no path traversal protection
In main.py:
pythonfilepath = os.path.join("/app/builds", filename)
If filename contains ../ sequences (e.g. ../app/auth.py), os.path.join will not protect against path traversal — it only anchors if the second argument is an absolute path. An unauthenticated attacker can read arbitrary files from the server filesystem via HTTP GET to /builds/../etc/passwd.
Fix:
pythonfilepath = os.path.realpath(os.path.join("/app/builds", filename))
if not filepath.startswith(os.path.realpath("/app/builds")):
    raise HTTPException(403)
27. /health endpoint accepts unauthenticated POST with arbitrary JSON keys that auto-create database columns
The _auto_migrate() function in health.py dynamically adds new SQLite columns for any unknown key in the health payload. A malicious device (or spoofed request) could add thousands of garbage columns, causing uncontrolled schema growth and eventual database corruption.
Fix: Whitelist all accepted keys with a hard-coded _ALLOWED_FIELDS set. Reject payloads with unrecognized keys rather than migrating them.

🟠 STABILITY ISSUES (Continued)
28. FTP file delay(1000) blocking call inside FreeRTOS task
cppdelay(1000); // Allow module to settle
Found in send_ftp_file(). Using Arduino delay() inside a FreeRTOS task blocks the task without yielding to the scheduler and prevents the WDT from being reset. All delays inside tasks must use vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000)).

29. OTA: malloc(65536) for the 64KB buffer — no fallback if heap is fragmented
cppuint8_t *buf = (uint8_t *)malloc(READ_SIZE);  // 65536 bytes
if (!buf) { ... Update.abort(); return; }
The guard for malloc failure is correct — but after a long uptime with multiple HTTP cycles, heap fragmentation can prevent a contiguous 64KB allocation even when total free heap exceeds 64KB. The OTA will silently fail with "malloc failed" and increment the fail counter.
Fix: Use a static uint8_t buf[65536] placed at global scope, or reduce chunk size to 4096 bytes which is always allocatable on a fragmented heap (at the cost of more round-trips per OTA).

30. OTA: ota_silent_mode = true set twice with no intervening reset path
cppota_silent_mode = true;  // Line ~4611 
// ... Update.begin() ...
ota_silent_mode = true;  // Line ~4634 (redundant comment says "Rule 50")
While functionally harmless, the redundant double-set obscures the code flow. More critically, if OTA fails between the two lines, ota_silent_mode remains true permanently (suppressing all debug output and GPRS logging), and the false restore is only reached if Update.begin() explicitly fails. The malloc failure path correctly resets it, but a corrupted total_no_of_bytes that passes the > 100000 check but fails Update.begin() correctly restores it too. This is actually handled, but the comment ota_silent_mode = false; // Fixed suggests it was previously broken, and the double-set makes auditing harder.

31. uCount static variable in backlog loop persists across calls
cppstatic int uCount = 0;
uCount++;
This counter inside the while (unsent_pointer_count < fileSize) loop in send_http_data() is static, so it accumulates across all 15-minute wakeup cycles forever. After ~2 billion records it overflows an int. More practically, it means the debug log "Line Number N" always shows an ever-increasing number that does not reset to 1 when a new backlog file is started. This is a debug logging nuisance but not a correctness bug.

🟡 EFFICIENCY IMPROVEMENTS (Continued)
32. BME280 bme.takeForcedMeasurement() holds i2cMutex for ~10ms
The BME280 in Forced Mode takes ~3–9ms for measurement completion (per Bosch datasheet). takeForcedMeasurement() in the Adafruit library includes a blocking wait loop internally. This is called while holding i2cMutex, blocking the RTC task and tempHum task. BME is only needed for pressure, so this doesn't affect primary weather data, but it adds I2C bus exclusion latency.
Fix: Use bme.setMode(MODE_FORCED) + bme.isMeasuring() poll without holding the mutex, only taking the mutex for the final register read.

33. reconstruct_sent_masks() / analyzeFileHealth() scans all SPIFFS files on every boot
These functions iterate the entire SPIFFS directory on every wake cycle. On a device with many small files (backlog fragments, GPS, signature), this SPIFFS scan takes measurable time on every 15-minute wakeup — adding to the active current draw period.
Recommendation: Cache the scan results in RTC RAM between wakeups. Only re-run the full scan on first boot or when firmwareUpdated is set.

34. loop() uses delay(500) — holds the Arduino loop task awake
cppdelay(500);  // in loop()
The loop() task (Arduino loopTask on Core 1) calls delay(500) unconditionally. While this does yield to FreeRTOS, it keeps loopTask scheduled every 500ms. Using vTaskDelay here is equivalent, but the loopTask itself could be suspended entirely after sleep entry with vTaskSuspend(NULL) to save the RTOS scheduling overhead.

