Firmware Review — Part 3 (Final)

🔴 SERVER-SIDE BUGS (Continued)
35. database.py intentionally excluded from version control — deployment risk
The README explicitly states: "database.py — DB connection (not stored here — on server)". This means deploy.sh's cp -r sync step will never copy or update database.py, so any change to the DB connection string (e.g., WAL mode, path, pool settings) must be made manually via SSH. This is a documented operational gap but a real deployment risk — a fresh server build has no database.py and the entire application fails to start with an ImportError. The file should be committed under version control (credentials can be kept in a .env file), or the deploy script must explicitly handle its absence.

36. _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE global is process-local and never invalidated
In health.py:
python_DB_COLUMNS_CACHE = None  # module-level global

def _auto_migrate(db, data, table="health_reports"):
    global _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE
    if _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE is None:
        _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE = _get_db_columns(db, table)
    ...
    _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE.add(key)  # Updates in-memory only
This cache is populated once per Python process and never invalidated. Two specific failures:

Multi-worker deployments: If uvicorn is run with --workers 2+ (or behind gunicorn), each worker has its own _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE. Worker A adds a new column and updates its cache, but Worker B's cache doesn't know about it. Worker B will attempt another ALTER TABLE on an already-existing column, which in SQLite raises OperationalError: duplicate column name. The current code catches this exception and calls _DB_COLUMNS_CACHE.add(key) — so it self-heals, but generates a database error log on every request from Worker B until its cache catches up.
Server restart after manual schema change: If someone manually drops a column or rolls back the DB to a schema snapshot, the cached set diverges from reality and _auto_migrate will silently fail to add it back.

Fix: Replace the module-level global with a per-request _get_db_columns() call, or use a proper SQLAlchemy inspect that queries the live schema. The performance cost on SQLite is negligible.

37. save_apn_config() in gprs_helpers.ino writes to SPIFFS without fsMutex
cppvoid save_apn_config(String apn, String ccid) {
  File f = SPIFFS.open("/apn_config.txt", FILE_WRITE);  // No mutex!
  if (f) { f.println(ccid); f.println(apn); f.close(); }
}
This function is called from send_at_cmd_data() (inside the GPRS task) at the moment of a successful HTTP send. The scheduler task also writes to SPIFFS at the same time (writing lastrecorded_*.txt, unsent.txt, etc.) under fsMutex. A concurrent write from the GPRS task (without the mutex) races with the scheduler's fsMutex-protected writes, risking SPIFFS directory corruption.
Fix: Add fsMutex acquisition at the start of save_apn_config(), or pass alreadyLocked=true from callers that already hold it.

38. Server OTA streaming uses blocking open() inside async generator — event loop starvation
In main.py:
pythonasync def iter_file():
    with open(filepath, "rb") as f:   # BLOCKING synchronous open!
        f.seek(start)
        ...
        await asyncio.sleep(0.5)       # yields, but the open() above blocked
Using synchronous open() and f.read() inside an async generator blocks the entire uvicorn event loop for the duration of each f.read() call. During a 2-minute OTA delivery (8 × 64KB chunks × 16s each), ALL other HTTP requests from ALL field devices are queued behind this single OTA delivery. With aiofiles already in requirements.txt, this is an easy fix.
Fix:
pythonimport aiofiles
async def iter_file():
    async with aiofiles.open(filepath, "rb") as f:
        await f.seek(start)
        ...
        await asyncio.sleep(0.5)

39. No rate limiting on POST /health — potential DoS vector
The /health endpoint is publicly accessible (no authentication required — by design, so field devices can report without credentials). However, there is no rate limiting. A single attacker with the endpoint URL can:

Flood the SQLite database with fake station check-ins (write amplification)
Trigger _auto_migrate schema changes at high rate
Fill the command_queue table via the timed-out retry logic

The stn_id field is the only identifier, and it accepts arbitrary strings. Fix: Add IP-based rate limiting using slowapi (already a common FastAPI extension) — e.g., 10 requests/minute per IP. Also add a maximum payload size check (currently FastAPI defaults to unlimited body size).

40. GET /cmd/{stn_id}/{command} in the README — the actual router uses POST
The README documents the command endpoint as GET /cmd/{stn_id}/{command}, but commands.py defines it as @router.post(...). The AuthMiddleware's protected prefixes include /cmd, so a GET request to /cmd/... would pass auth but hit a 405 Method Not Allowed. If anyone built tooling against the documented GET interface, it silently fails with a non-obvious error. This is a documentation bug but can cause operator confusion during field interventions.

🟠 DEEPER FIRMWARE STABILITY ISSUES
41. verify_bearer_or_recover() can block for up to 85 seconds holding bearer_recovery_active = true
The recovery sequence includes:

Up to 60s waiting for re-registration (30 × 2s loop)
5s settle time
Up to 20s more for radio refresh and re-registration

Total worst-case: ~85 seconds. During this entire window, bearer_recovery_active = true, which suppresses all debugln() output. More critically, the tempHum task and lcdkeypad tasks check bearer_recovery_active indirectly via the debug macros — their output is suppressed, but they still run. The scheduler, however, could be attempting to read sensor data and log it while the modem is in AT+CFUN=0 (radio off), causing I2C activity on a potentially unstable bus.

42. goto bearer_recovery: label in gprs_helpers.ino is inside a block-scoped if
cppif (context_active) {
    // ... IP check ...
    goto bearer_recovery;  // jumps OUT of this if-block
}
bearer_recovery:            // target label is outside the if-block
This goto jumps from inside the if (context_active) block to a label defined outside it. In C++, jumping over variable declarations is undefined behavior if any initialized variables are declared between the goto and the label. In this specific case, the intervening code only has a String deact_cmd (which IS declared before the goto), so it works — but it depends on the variable being declared before the jump, which is easy to accidentally break in future edits. The comment // Label used for ghost-session fallthrough helps but this pattern should be refactored into a helper function.

43. content global String used as a shared buffer between scheduler and GPRS tasks
cppextern String content;  // in globals.h
content is written by the scheduler task (content = file1.readStringUntil('\n')) and also used/modified in the GPRS task's backlog loop (charArray = content.c_str()). Although the scheduler writes it before signaling the GPRS task, there is no explicit memory barrier or mutex protecting this String. On a dual-core ESP32, Core 0 (GPRS) reading content.c_str() while Core 1 (Scheduler) is potentially modifying it (e.g., in a concurrent readStringUntil) is a data race. Arduino String is not thread-safe.
Fix: Replace content global with a char content_buf[160] protected by fsMutex, consistent with all other shared file buffers in the system.

44. Scheduler SKIP_START_GAPS label destination is inside a nested conditional
cppgoto SKIP_START_GAPS;
// ... skipped code ...
SKIP_START_GAPS:
This follows the same goto-based control flow pattern as TRIGGER_HTTP (Issue #9). The goto SKIP_START_GAPS is used to bypass gap-fill record creation when a fresh boot or valid record already exists. While the hoisted declarations at the loop top prevent scope errors, the pattern creates a hidden assumption that all state variables are in a known state when the label is hit. Any future developer adding initialization code between the goto and the label will produce silent state bugs.

45. diag_consecutive_reg_fails reset happens on FTP success but not HTTP retry success
cpp// In send_ftp_file() success path:
diag_consecutive_reg_fails = 0;  // RESET counter on any successful data upload
The counter is correctly reset on FTP success. But in send_at_cmd_data() (HTTP success path), it is NOT reset. This means: if HTTP primary send fails (counter goes to 1), but a backlog retry succeeds — the counter stays at 1. On the next cycle, diag_consecutive_http_fails >= 2 check triggers an unnecessary AT+CIPSHUT deep reset. The consecutive fails counter should be reset on ANY successful data delivery (HTTP or FTP).

🟡 EFFICIENCY IMPROVEMENTS (Continued)
46. Server-side OTA throttle degrades from 4KB/s to effectively less due to TCP overhead
The asyncio.sleep(0.5) between each 2KB chunk introduces not just a delay but also a TCP segment boundary. The modem's HTTP client on the A7672S receives each 2KB segment as a separate TCP push, triggering an ACK round-trip for every segment. Over 2G with a 500ms RTT, this alone adds 500ms per 2KB — doubling the intended throttle. The effective throughput becomes ~2KB/s instead of ~4KB/s, doubling OTA time to ~4 minutes. The throttle should be recalibrated — serving 8KB chunks with a single 500ms delay would give the same effective rate with fewer TCP round-trips.

47. CommandQueue timed-out entries accumulate indefinitely in the database
The server retries commands that haven't received feedback after 3 hours. But completed commands (with executed_at and completed_at set) are never pruned. Over a fleet's lifetime, the command_queue table grows without bound. The planned Phase 4 includes "auto-clear for executed commands older than 7 days" — but this should be implemented now as a startup cleanup task, not deferred.
Fix (one-liner in main.py startup):
pythondb.query(CommandQueue).filter(
    CommandQueue.completed_at < datetime.utcnow() - timedelta(days=7)
).delete()

48. Battery voltage read timing: ADC2 blocked by WiFi even when wifi_active = false if WiFi was not fully disabled
The ADC2 (GPIO 25, solar) read is guarded by if (!wifi_active && !gprs_started). However, ESP32's ADC2 is hardware-blocked whenever the WiFi RF calibration logic is running, not just when WiFi is "active" from the software perspective. If WiFi was enabled and then WiFi.disconnect() was called, the RF calibration may still be running for a few hundred milliseconds. During this window, adc2_get_raw() returns ESP_ERR_TIMEOUT silently (the code checks == ESP_OK), causing solar_val to retain its stale previous value rather than reading 0. This is a minor accuracy issue but means solar readings during WiFi transitions are unreliable.

